{
    "word": "Indolence",
    "definitions": [
        "Freedom from that which pains, or harasses, as toil, care, grief, etc.",
        "The quality or condition of being indolent; inaction, or lack of exertion of body or mind, proceeding from love of ease or aversion to toil; habitual idleness; indisposition to labor; laziness; sloth; inactivity."
    ],
    "examples": [
        "I have ease, if it may not rather be called indolence.",
        "Life spent in indolence, and therefore sad.",
        "As there is a great truth wrapped up in indolenceindolence is thus a state in which we have no grief or pain; so that the word, as we now employ it, seems to affirm that indulgence in sloth and ease is that which would constitute for us the absence of all pain."
    ],
    "etymology": "[L. indolentia freedom from pain: cf. F. indolence.]"
}